{{Infobox book | italic title = <!--(see above)--> | name = | image = File:Copertina "Dialogo de Cecco di Ronchitti da Bruzene in Perpuosito de la stella Nuova".jpg | border = yes | image_size = | caption = Title page of first (Paduan) edition | alt = | author = attributed to [[Galileo Galilei]] or Girolamo Spinelli or both as co-authors | title_orig = Dialogo de Cecco di Ronchitti da Bruzene in perpuosito de la stella Nuova | orig_lang_code = vec | title_working = | translator = | illustrator = | cover_artist = | language = Paduan dialect | series = | subject = | genre = | published = {{plainlist| * 1605 by Pietro Paolo<ref>On the title page of this edition the second part of the publisher's forename appears in the much less common form "Paulo", a dialectal variant of "Paolo" from the Latin "Paulus".</ref> Tozzi, [[Padua]] (1st ed.) * 1605 by Bartolomeo Merlo, [[Verona]] (2nd ed.)}} | media_type = | pages = | awards = | isbn = | oclc = | dewey = | congress = | preceded_by = | followed_by = | native_external_url = https://openlibrary.org/books/OL16846993M/Dialogo_de_Cecco_di_Ronchitti_..._in_perpvosito_de_la_stella_nvova | native_external_host = the [[Open library]] | exclude_cover = }}
'''''Dialogo de Cecco di Ronchitti da Bruzene in perpuosito de la stella Nuova''''' (''Dialogue of Cecco di Ronchitti of [[Brugine]] concerning the New star'') is the title of an early 17th-century [[pseudonym|pseudonymous]] [[pamphlet]] ridiculing the views of an aspiring [[Aristotelianism|Aristotelian philosopher]], Antonio Lorenzini da Montepulciano,<ref>Favaro ([[#CITEREFFavaro,_AntonioGalileiSpinelli1881|1881]], [https://archive.org/stream/attidelrealeist03unkngoog#page/n242/mode/1up pp.210''ff'']). Lorenzini had espoused his views in a booklet, ''Discorso intorno alla nuova stella'', published in Padua at the beginning of 1605</ref> on the nature and properties of [[Kepler's Supernova]], which had appeared in October 1604. The pseudonymous ''Dialogue'' was written in the coarse language of a rustic Paduan dialect,<ref>Drake ([[#CITEREFDrakeGalileiSpinelli1976|1976]], pp.ix, 23–24, 45)</ref> and first published in about March, 1605, in [[Padua]]. A second edition was published later the same year in [[Verona]].<ref>Favaro ([[#CITEREFFavaro,_AntonioGalileiSpinelli1881|1881]], [https://archive.org/stream/attidelrealeist03unkngoog#page/n227/mode/1up pp.195–237]), Drake ([[#CITEREFDrakeGalileiSpinelli1976|1976]], pp.1–32).</ref> A translation into standard Italian was published by [[:it:Antonio Favaro|Antonio Favaro]]<ref>Favaro ([[#CITEREFFavaro,_AntonioGalileiSpinelli1881|1881]], [https://archive.org/stream/attidelrealeist03unkngoog#page/n271/mode/1up pp.239–271])</ref> in 1881, and an English translation by [[Stillman Drake]]<ref>Drake ([[#CITEREFDrakeGalileiSpinelli1976|1976]], pp.33–53)</ref> in 1976.
Scholars agree that the pamphlet was written either by [[Galileo Galilei]] or one of his followers, Girolamo Spinelli, or by both in collaboration, but do not agree on the extent of the contribution&mdash;if any&mdash;made by each of them to its composition.
