'''Gerald C. MacCallum Jr.''' (June 16, 1925 – January 14, 1987) was an American philosopher. He was Professor of Philosophy at the [[University of Wisconsin–Madison]].<ref>{{cite journal|author=William H. Hay|author2=Rex Martin|author3=Marcus Singer|last-author-amp=yes|title=Gerald C. MacCallum, Jr. 1925–1987|journal=Proceedings and Addresses of the American Philosophical Association|date=November 1987|volume=61|issue=2|pages=383}}</ref>
MacCallum is well known for his critique to the distinction, made famous by [[Isaiah Berlin]], between [[Negative liberty|negative]] and [[positive liberty]], proposing instead that the concept of freedom can only be understood as a 'triadic relation', in which "'''x''' is (is not) free from '''y''' to do (not do, become, not become) '''z'''".<ref>{{cite journal|last=MacCallum|first=Gerald C.|title=Negative and Positive Freedom|journal=The Philosophical Review|date=July 1967|volume=76|issue=3|pages=314|doi=10.2307/2183622}}</ref>
